Quick Sambar Rice Recipe -
Ven pongal - 1 portion/ 1 cup
Ghee - 2 tbsp
Mustard Seeds - 1/4 tsp
Curry Leaves - 1 sprig
Dry Red Chilli - 1 no.
Peanuts (whole, with skin) - 2 tbsp
Shallots - 15-20 nos
Tomato - 1 no.
Carrot - 1 no.
Beans - 5-7 nos
Drumstick - 1 no.
Cookd Lunch Sambar Masala - 1 sachet
Coriander Leaves (Garnish)
Heat 1 tbsp ghee in a pot. Add mustard seeds, curry leaves, red chilli and peanuts. Fry well.
Add the shallots and fry for 2 mins.
Add the tomato and other vegetables. Fry for 3-4 mins.
Add 1/2 sachet of Cookd Lunch Sambar Masala. Mix well.
Add water and boil for 7-8 mins until the vegetables are tender.
Add the ven pongal and mix well. Cook for 3-5 mins until it it mixed well.
Finish with chopped coriander leaves and ghee. Serve hot with appalam

Sakkarai Pongal Pradhaman Recipe -
Sakkarai pongal - 1 portion/ 1 cup
Coconut milk - 1 tetra
Jaggery/ Jaggery powder - 1/2 cup
Cardamom Pods/ Powder - 2-3 nos
Ghee - 1-2 tsp
Nendran Banana - 1no.
Cashew nuts (half/ pcs) - 15-20 pcs
Raisins
Coconut bits (fresh/ copra)
Heat ghee in a kadai. Fry the cashew, raisins and coconut till golden brown and remove.
Add the crushes cardamom pods and chopped nendran banana. Fry till soft.
Add jaggery and water and dissolve. (You can strain if you see particles)
Add the sakkarai pongal and mix well.
Add coconut milk and the fried nuts back.
Bring it to a simmer and switch off the flame.
The payasam can be served hot or cold.

Some of my most memorable food experiences, across places and cultures 😍
Wherever I go, food always becomes my biggest inspiration. It’s never just about eating, it’s about watching, learning, understanding the culture behind it.

Japan was a real eye-opener for me. From steaming hot gyoza to watching an 80-year-old chef make tempura right in front of me, showing me exactly how it should be eaten. That kind of respect for food stays with you 🍤
Italy was pure joy. My first gelato, Fior di Latte. Just milk, done right. Simple, honest, unforgettable 🍦

And then closer home, Pune. That kala mutton at Jagdambh. So powerful, so rooted, I had to come back and recreate it on YFL. And the love it received said everything ❤️

India will always be unmatched, but these journeys across kitchens and cultures have taught me so much.
Loved sharing these stories with Gulshan Devaiyah.
Because no matter where I go, food is always the starting point. ✈️🍽️

Cooked my ‘Secret Mutton Curry’ Recipe with the brilliant and charming @gulshandevaiah78 🔥
What a joy it was cooking together. So many conversations around food, culture, movies and everything in between.

From the comforting flavours of Bengali cuisine to the bold zest of Greek dishes, a little Coorg magic and even some Kantara-inspired moments… the kitchen was full of laughter, stories and really good food 😍

And yes, my “Secret Mutton Curry” isn’t a secret anymore.

APEDA, under the Ministry of Commerce & Industry, in collaboration with the Government of Meghalaya and IFOAM Organics Asia, organised the first-ever North East India Organic Week & Buyer Seller Meet in Shillong, with an aim to connect the organic strength of the North Eastern Region to larger markets.

The event brought together farmers, producer groups, buyers and exporters, opening new markets and export opportunities for the region.

We were there to witness these connections take shape and are excited to share the experience with you. The video drops today at 6 PM today so stay tuned.

A night built on balance, nuance, and a table of people who know how to sit with both.

For Serious Eaters Dinner #3, we took over @grammie.del to explore Wafu,  not Western, not fully Japanese, but comfortably in between. A style of cooking shaped by contrast rather than force, borrowing freely, blending thoughtfully, and never losing the point.

The courses arrived unhurried. Dishes that felt familiar at first, then shifted a few bites in. Grounded flavours with restless ideas behind them, and technique that stayed quiet and precise. Food you eat a little slower, best paired with an ice-cold @suntorytoki highball keeping the table easy.

This was Wafu as it should be: fluid, modern, and personal.

Conversation outlasted the courses. Glasses kept getting topped up. And somewhere between plates, strangers turned into people who stayed till the last sip.

This is why the Serious Eaters Club exists,  for curious appetites, open tables, and dinners you don’t rush through.

If this feels like your kind of table, you know where to be.
The Serious Eaters Club Broadcast Channel is where the next one drops.

#Foodtalkindia #seriouseatersclub #wafu #delhifoodie

Serious Eaters Club came together again, this time at @grammie.del for a night shaped by Wafu.
Neither Western nor fully Japanese, but something far more intuitive. A cuisine that borrows, blends, and bends the rules without ever losing its soul.

Season 2, Dinner #3 unfolded through plates that felt familiar yet surprising, rooted yet restless. Thoughtful flavours, quiet technique, and dishes that revealed themselves slowly and best enjoyed with time, curiosity, and an ice cold @suntorytoki highball in hand.

This was Wafu as it’s meant to be experienced: fluid, modern, and deeply personal. Where conversations stretched longer than courses, and the table did what it always does, turned strangers into people who stayed till the last sip.

As 2025 comes to a close, Delhi Food Walks is delighted to introduce the DFW Membership Program—a new initiative aimed at creating a deeper, more meaningful bond with our community of food lovers, culture enthusiasts, and storytellers.

You need to ‘FIX YOUR OIL!!’ 🤔

Ever wondered why some dishes taste extra good? It’s the oil 😉
Oil is a flavour magnet, so when it’s pure, your food gets richer aroma, better taste and real nutrients. Unlike most of the refined oils that go through harsh processing. On the other hand ‘Cold Pressed Oils’ keep it simple and natural.

That’s why Tata Simply Better Cold Pressed Oils are my go-to, natural, hexane-free, flavourful and perfect for everyday cooking. Every bottle has its own personality and works beautifully across multiple dishes ✨

If you want a list of which oil suits which recipe, comment “Simply better” and I’ll send it to you personally 💛

60-Minute vs 3 Hour vs 12 Hour DAL MAKHANI Series EP 3 | Chef Sanjyot Keer
This is the 12-hour slow-cooked version - the finale of my exclusive Facebook series! 🔥
This is how Dal Makhani was traditionally made, back when people had the patience and the skill to use the tandoor’s residual heat at night for better fuel efficiency.
The result? A magical, melt-in-mouth Dal Makhani.

A gentle coal fire.
A pot that barely bubbles.
Hours of starch breaking down naturally.
By morning, the dal turns silky, dark, and almost glossy on its own.
Same ingredients as Episode 1, but the texture, aroma, and richness are on another level.

To wrap the series, I compare all three! The 60-minute, the 3-hour, and the 12-hour version. 🔥

Time changes Dal Makhani in ways you have to taste to believe.
Would you ever try cooking Dal Makhani for over 12 hours?

60-Minute vs 3 Hour vs 12 Hour DAL MAKHANI series EP 2 | Chef Sanjyot Keer
Back with Episode 2 of my Facebook exclusive Dal Makhani series 🔥

Today we move from “quick”… to “slow enough to taste the difference.”
A 3-hour simmer changes everything — deeper colour, softer aroma, and that gentle starch release you simply don’t get in a pressure cooker.

The potli works its magic.
The slow simmer builds a rounder, fuller flavour.
Same ingredients. More patience.
A Dal Makhani that feels a little closer to the classic.

Watch Episode 3, where I cook the dal for over 12 hours and we finally answer the big question:
Does slow cooking actually change the game?

Fried Chicken Biriyani Recipe😋😍👇🏼
Ingredients (Serves 5)
1. Chicken – 1 kg, cut into medium pieces
2. Turmeric powder – 1/2 tsp
Kashmiri chili powder – 1 - 1.5 tbsp
Pepper powder – 1/2 tsp
Garam masala powder – 1 tbsp (recipe below)
Yoghurt - 2 tbsp
Lemon juice - 2 tsp 
Salt – As required
3. Oil – As required to fry
4. Onion – 2 cups, deep-fried till golden and crisp
5. Cashews and raisins – 1/4 each, deep fried
6. Oil – 3 – 4 tbsp
7. Onion – 2 medium-large, thinly sliced and halved (Around 1.5 cup)
8. Ginger -1 inch, roughly chopped 
Garlic- 6-8 medium cloves, chopped 
Green chilies – 6-8, chopped 
Crush ginger, garlic and green chilies in the small jar of a blender.
9. Turmeric powder – 1/2 tsp
Kashmiri chili powder (good quality) - 1 tbsp 
Coriander powder- 2 tsp 
Garam masala powder- 1 tbsp
10. Tomato, ripe – 3 small, thinly sliced 
11. Curd – 1/2 cup
12. Cilantro – 3 tbsp, chopped
Mint leaves – 3 tbsp, chopped
13. Hot water – 1/3 - 1/2 cup 
14. Salt – To taste
For the rice
15. Jeerakashala rice / kaima rice – 3 cups, rinsed
16. Ghee – 2 tbsp + oil - 1 -2 tbsp
17. Whole spices – Green cardamom – 4, cloves – 6, cinnamon stick – 1 inch broken, bay leaves – 2, mace – 1/2 of one
Salt – To taste
18. Hot water – 6 cups
To layer
17. Fried onion, cashews and raisins
Cilantro – 1/2 cup, chopped
Mint leaves –  1/2 cup, chopped
Garam masala powder – Few pinches
Ghee – 1 – 2 tbsp
Rose water – 1/4 – 1/2 tsp
(Contd in comment)

Vegetable Pulao with Chicken Roast (Recipe below👇🏼)
Ingredients 
1. Chicken, bone-in - 1 -1.5 kg
2. ⁠Turmeric powder - 3/4 tsp
Kashmiri chili powder (good quality) - 1 - 1.5 tbsp 
Coriander powder- 3/4 tsp
Garam masala powder- 1 tsp
Yoghurt- 2 tbsp
Fried onion - 3/4 cup (thinly slice and deep fry onion till browned)
Curry leaves- 1 sprig 
Salt 
3. Coconut oil - 3 tbsp 
4. ⁠Onion - 2 cup, thinly sliced 
5. ⁠Ginger garlic paste - 1.5 tbsp
6. ⁠Tomatoes- 2 medium small
7. ⁠Garam masala powder- 1/2 - 3/4 tsp
8. ⁠Salt
Method
1. Combine chicken with all the ingredients numbered 2. Let rest for 2 hrs. 
2. ⁠Heat oil and add onion, curry leaves and a pinch of salt. Cook till onion turns light golden. Add ginger garlic paste and cook for a few minutes. Add tomatoes and cook till mashed up. Add marinated chicken and mix well. Cook covered for 25-30 mts, stirring in between. Add a pinch of sugar and 1/2 tsp garam masala powder. Switch off. Serve with pulao/chapathi etc.

Malabar Coconut Rice with Easy Pan grilled Chicken Roast (Recipe below)👇🏼 
Pan Grilled Chicken Roast Recipe 
Ingredients
1. Chicken leg quarters – 3 
2. Turmeric powder – 1/2 tsp
Kashmiri chili powder – 1 tbsp
Garam masala powder – 1/2 tsp
Pepper powder – 1/2 tsp
Lemon juice- 1 tbsp
Oil - 1 tbsp
Salt
3. Oil – 1 + 3 tbsp
4. Onion – 2.5 cup, thinly sliced and halved
Curry leaves - 2 sprig
5. Ginger and garlic, crushed - 2 tsp each or 2 tsp ginger garlic paste
6. Turmeric powder – 1/2 tsp
Kashmiri chili powder (good quality)– 1.5 tsp
Garam masala powder – 3/4 tsp
Pepper powder – 1/4 – 1/2 tsp
Method
1. Combine the chicken leg quarters with ingredients numbered 2. Let rest for 2 hrs.2. Heat 2 tbsp oil and place the chicken leg quarters. Cook covered on med flame for about 5-10 minutes till the bottom part is browned. Flip to the other side and cook covered for 10-15 mts till the chicken is completely cooked through. Remove to a plate. Transfer the gravy to a bowl to use later.
3. Add more oil to the pan and add onion and little salt. Cook till light golden. Add a few curry leaves, crushed ginger garlic and cook for a few minutes till their raw smell is completely gone. Add spice powders numbered 7 and cook for 1-2 mts. Sprinkle a little water. Mix well. Add fried chicken leg quarters and coat well with the masala. Cook on both sides over low medium heat for 2-3 minutes. Sprinkle coriander leaves and serve hot.
.

🔸Chilli Chicken (Recipe below)
Chilli Chicken 
Ingredients (Serves 4 – 5)

1. Boneless chicken, preferably thighs – Around 1/2 - 3/4 kg, cut into small pieces
Chilli powder – 3/4 tsp
Freshly ground pepper powder – 1/2 tsp
Salt – 1/2 tsp
Corn starch– 3 tbsp
All purpose flour – 3 tbsp
Egg – 1, beaten
Soy sauce – 1 tsp
2. Oil – To deep-fry
For the gravy
3. Vegetable oil – 2 tbsp
4. Dried red chilies – 2, broken
Onion – 3/4 cup, finely chopped 
5. Onion - 1/2 cup, cubed
Ginger – 3/4 tsp, minced
Garlic – 2 tsp, minced
Green chilies – 2 , diagonally sliced
6. Green or red chilli sauce or chilli-garlic sauce – 1.5 - 2 tbsp
Soy sauce, light – 2 - 3 tsp
Soy sauce, dark – 2 tsp
Tomato ketchup – 2.5 tbsp
Sugar – 1/2 tsp
Pepper powder, freshly ground – 1/2 tsp
7. Corn flour / corn starch – 1.5 tsp mixed in 2 tbsp water, for thickening the gravy ( I used Argo corn starch)
8. Chicken Stock / Water – 1/2 – 3/4 cup
9. Salt – To taste, add only if required as the sauces are already salty
Butter – 2 – 3 tsp, for extra taste
Spring onion – 1/4 cup, to garnish

Method
1. Combine chicken thighs with the remaining ingredients numbered 1. Set aside for 30 mts. Deep fry in 2 – 3 batches until golden, takes about 4 – 6 minutes, over medium-high heat. Drain on to a paper towel.

Two-in-One Chicken Curry for busy days 👇🏼
Step 1: Prepare a Large Batch of Chicken Curry (I cooked Kerala style spicy chicken curry, recipe in comments section).
Step 2: Divide the curry into two portions
First Portion: Add in medium thick coconut milk and simmer for a minute. This curry pairs wonderfully with chapathi or appam.
Second Portion: Pepper Chicken Roast
Transfer the second portion of chicken curry to a wok.
 Add pepper powder, chopped cilantro, and sliced green chilies.
Stir for a few minutes until the curry is semi-dry.
Add a teaspoon of butter for extra taste. This variation complements pulao or any rice dish and chapathis.
It not only saves time but also ensures you have diverse flavors for a couple of days.

Kala jeera / shahi jeera – 1/4 tsp
Mace / jathi pathri – 1/2
Powder the above ingredients and use in the recipe. Store any leftovers in an air tight container.
For the rice
12. Jeerakashala rice / kaima – 2.5 cup
13. Ghee – 2 tbsp
Whole spices – Green cardamom – 4, fennel seeds – 1 pinch, cloves – 6, cinnamon stick – 3/4 inch, whole black pepper corns – 1/2 tsp
14. Salt – To taste
15. Hot water – 5 cup (For 1 cup rice, use 2 cups of water)
To garnish
Fried onion
Rose water – 1/2 tsp (optional)
Ghee - 1.5 tbsp
Fried cashews and raisins – 3 tbsp each

A night built on fire, flavour, and a table full of people who know how to appreciate both.

For Serious Eaters Dinner #2, we took the club to Niko for Kasei: born of flame, a menu shaped by heat in every form.

We opened with a duck miso ramen layered with a soy mirin egg and slow cooked duck chashu, followed by torched tuna dressed in smoked buttermilk yuzu and tanuki. Then came the charred prawn, enriched with prawn butter, coriander ponzu, kimchi mayo, a whisper of Toki whisky, and Hokkaido milk bread that didn’t last long.

Course four brought the robata: kaffir corn, pork char siu, and chicken tsukune, each one kissed by flame and perfectly paired with a Jasmine Toki Highball, light, fragrant, and exactly what the moment needed.

The scorched salmon miso and its 1000 layer potato drew the kind of silence you only get when something is genuinely exceptional. And the matcha crème brûlée closed the evening with a nod to those who love their greens in every form.

Nights like these are why the Serious Eaters Club exists, curious hungry people who show up for food that sparks conversation and leaves a mark.

If this looks like your kind of table, consider this your sign.

How to enter:
 - Join the Serious Eaters Broadcast Channel

 Real food, real people, real good whisky. 🥢🥃

Throwback to a seriously memorable night at the Serious Eaters Club: our Nikkei dinner at Atticus brought together a room full of people who live for good food, great stories, and even better company.

We sat down to a menu that moved beautifully across Peru and Japan: crispy lotus stem with salsa to open the night, bright and sharp Tiradito, the reconstructed dumpling that had everyone talking, the Lomo Saltado that disappeared faster than we expected, and finally that silky avocado cheesecake with chilli-lime curd that wrapped the evening perfectly.
